latestPosts.caption:
In Japan, chopstick etiquette is taken seriously and reflects respect for tradition, others, and the meal itself. Understanding and following these customs is important for several reasons:

Why Chopstick Etiquette Matters in Japan

1. Respect for Culture and Tradition

Japanese dining customs are deeply rooted in centuries-old traditions. Observing proper chopstick use shows awareness and appreciation of Japanese culture.

2. Politeness and Consideration for Others

Manners are a core part of Japanese social interaction. Using chopsticks properly prevents discomfort or offense at the table.

3. Avoiding Associations with Death

Certain chopstick actions mimic funeral rituals and are considered taboo. For example:
	•	Passing food from chopsticks to chopsticks mirrors a cremation ritual.
	•	Sticking chopsticks upright in rice resembles offerings made to the dead.

4. Promoting Cleanliness and Order

Good etiquette helps keep the dining experience clean and pleasant, such as not pointing with chopsticks or not licking them.

latestPosts.caption:
Japan now has an official Hello Kitty-themed airport. As of April 13, 2025, Oita Airport in Kunisaki, Oita Prefecture, has been temporarily renamed Oita Hello Kitty Airport to coincide with Expo 2025 in Osaka. 

The airport features extensive Hello Kitty and Sanrio decorations, themed signage, photo spots, and exclusive merchandise like keychains, T-shirts, and cookies. Travelers also receive Sanrio-themed luggage tags upon departure. A new bus service now connects the airport to Harmonyland, a Sanrio theme park located about an hour away. 

This initiative, running until October 13, 2025, aims to boost tourism to Oita Prefecture, known for its famous hot springs, and to distribute tourist traffic more evenly across Japan during the Expo. 🎀

latestPosts.caption:
Every year, around 80,000 people in Japan vanish, a phenomenon known as Johatsu, or “the evaporated.” Driven by financial struggles, family conflicts, or work pressure, they choose to disappear and start fresh elsewhere, often to escape debt, troubled relationships, or the shame of failure. 

Some seek help from night-moving services—specialized companies that secretly relocate them, erase their digital footprints, and help them avoid detection. While many disappearances are voluntary, Johatsu highlights deeper social and economic issues in Japan, where the pressure to conform often leaves people feeling that vanishing is their only option. 🎌

latestPosts.caption: A new SEGA STORE TOKYO is opening on July 18th, 2025, in Shibuya PARCO, Japan. This will be SEGA's first main store in Japan, following a successful opening in Shanghai. The store will offer exclusive merchandise, including special Sonic the Hedgehog figures, and feature futuristic displays. To celebrate the opening, customers who spend over 7,000 JPY will receive a free tumbler, and Sonic the Hedgehog himself will be there from July 18th to 21st. The store aims to be a major spot for pop culture fans in Shibuya.

latestPosts.caption:
@maya_hangai shows us 3 products you must have to survive summer in Japan ☀️🇯🇵

💡More Tips to Survive Summer in Japan ☀️🇯🇵:

1. Stay Hydrated – Always carry a water bottle; vending machines are everywhere.
2. Use a Cooling Towel – Popular and sold at most convenience stores.
3. Wear Breathable Clothes – Go for loose, light cotton or linen.
4. Avoid Midday Heat – Sightsee early morning or after sunset.
5. Use Sunscreen – The UV index gets intense!	
6. Seek Shade Often – Rest in konbini, malls, or station areas.
7. Use a Portable Fan – Many people carry handheld or neck fans.
8. Eat Light & Cool Meals – Try somen, kakigori, or cold soba.
9. Use Parasols or Hats – Common in Japan and super effective.
10. Watch Out for Heatstroke Signs – Dizziness, nausea = cool down immediately.

latestPosts.caption: Japan is setting a new goal to move power lines underground and remove utility poles in cities, especially along emergency routes, by 2030. This aims to prevent poles from falling during disasters and blocking roads, while also improving city appearance. They'll also look for cheaper ways to do this work.
